<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Constantine_I&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<p>Essays from <i>The Cambridge Companion to the Age of Constantine</i> are marked with a "(CC)".</p>
<div class="references-small references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width:30em; column-width:30em;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-birthdate-0">^ <a href="#cite_ref-birthdate_0-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-birthdate_0-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Birth dates vary but most modern historians use c. 272". Lenski, "Reign of Constantine" (CC), 59.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> In (<a href="/wiki/Latin_language" title="Latin language" class="mw-redirect">Latin</a> Constantine's official imperial title was <small>IMPERATOR CAESAR FLAVIVS CONSTANTINVS PIVS FELIX INVICTVS AVGVSTVS</small>, <i>Imperator Caesar Flavius Constantine Augustus, the pious, the fortunate, the undefeated</i>. After 312, he added <small>MAXIMVS</small> ("the greatest"), and after 325 replaced ("undefeated") with <small>VICTOR</small>, as <i>invictus</i> reminded of <a href="/wiki/Sol_Invictus" title="Sol Invictus">Sol Invictus</a>, the Sun God.</li>
